      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Nitroglycerin (Nitrostat) 0.4 mg SL PRN</strong></td>
          <td>Nitrate vasodilator</td>
          <td>First-line angina treatment. Onset 1–3 minutes SL. Check BP before every dose — <strong>HOLD if SBP &lt; 90 mmHg</strong>. Hold if recent PDE-5 inhibitor (sildenafil, tadalafil) use. Sit/lie patient before giving. Expect headache (very common — expected side effect). May repeat q5 min × 3 doses; if no relief after 3 doses → notify provider STAT (possible MI). Store in amber glass bottle away from heat/light/moisture.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Oxygen via nasal cannula</strong></td>
          <td>Supportive therapy</td>
          <td>Titrate to SpO₂ ≥ 94%. Reduces myocardial O₂ demand by improving arterial oxygen content. Wean when SpO₂ ≥ 94% on room air. Assess nasal mucosa for dryness with prolonged use; consider humidified O₂ at higher flow rates.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Aspirin 81–325 mg PO daily</strong></td>
          <td>Antiplatelet agent</td>
          <td>Prevents platelet aggregation at site of atherosclerotic plaque. Cornerstone of CAD management. Take with food to reduce GI irritation. Do not stop without provider instruction — abrupt discontinuation increases clot risk. Report unusual bleeding or GI symptoms.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Metoprolol (beta-blocker) PO</strong></td>
          <td>Selective beta-1 adrenergic blocker</td>
          <td>Reduces heart rate and myocardial O₂ demand — directly therapeutic for angina. Monitor HR before administration — hold if HR &lt; 60 bpm per protocol. Monitor BP — hold if SBP &lt; 90. <strong>Do NOT stop abruptly</strong> — rebound tachycardia and angina/MI can occur. Patient teaching: change positions slowly (orthostatic hypotension risk).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Atorvastatin (statin) PO</strong></td>
          <td>HMG-CoA reductase inhibitor (statin)</td>
          <td>Lowers LDL cholesterol; stabilizes atherosclerotic plaques; reduces inflammation. Take at night (hepatic cholesterol synthesis peaks at night). Monitor liver function tests. Report muscle pain, weakness, or dark urine (myopathy/rhabdomyolysis — rare but serious). Avoid grapefruit juice — inhibits statin metabolism.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
