  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Which finding causes the nurse to HOLD sublingual NTG?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>SBP &lt; 90 mmHg.</strong> Nitroglycerin is a potent vasodilator. If administered to a hypotensive patient, vasodilation worsens hypotension → reduced coronary perfusion pressure → decreased myocardial O₂ delivery → worsening ischemia and risk of cardiovascular collapse. Check BP before every dose. Also hold for recent PDE-5 inhibitor use, severe aortic stenosis, or right ventricular infarction.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: What is the medication of choice for initial angina relief and how does it work?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Sublingual nitroglycerin 0.4 mg.</strong> Onset: 1–3 minutes (fastest route for angina relief). Mechanism: releases nitric oxide → smooth muscle relaxation → vasodilation → (1) dilates coronary arteries = increases myocardial O₂ supply; (2) dilates venous capacitance vessels = decreases preload = decreases O₂ demand. The dual mechanism addresses both sides of the supply-demand imbalance simultaneously.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: After 3 doses of NTG with no relief, what does the nurse do?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Notify the provider immediately via SBAR.</strong> Three doses of NTG without relief indicates possible unstable angina or acute MI — a medical emergency. Immediately: call provider, obtain 12-lead ECG (look for ST elevation = STEMI), obtain troponin (elevated in MI), ensure IV access and continuous cardiac monitoring. If STEMI on ECG, activate cardiac catheterization lab protocol. Document time of symptom onset — "door to balloon" time matters for STEMI outcomes.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: How does calming an anxious patient directly reduce angina?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Anxiety → sympathetic activation → catecholamine release → tachycardia → increased myocardial O₂ demand → worsens ischemia.</strong> Reducing anxiety through calm, reassuring communication reduces sympathetic drive → lower heart rate → decreased O₂ consumption → reduced ischemia. This is a direct physiological intervention, not simply a comfort measure. Reassurance is therapeutic in angina management.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: Which secondary diagnosis most increases Grace's risk of silent ischemia and why?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Diabetes mellitus.</strong> Chronic hyperglycemia causes autonomic and sensory neuropathy that impairs cardiac pain perception. Diabetic patients may experience significant myocardial ischemia — including MI — without the classic warning pain of angina. This is called <strong>silent ischemia</strong>. For Grace, this means: (1) she may underreport or not notice worsening angina; (2) the nurse must not rely solely on patient report and must monitor objective data (vital signs, ECG changes, SpO₂); (3) the actual degree of ischemia may be greater than her pain rating suggests.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q6: How does angina differ from unstable angina and acute MI?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div>
            <h4>✅ Stable Angina (Grace's diagnosis)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Predictable — triggered by exertion or stress</li>
              <li>Temporary, reversible ischemia — no cell death</li>
              <li>Duration: 1–5 minutes</li>
              <li>Relieved by rest and/or NTG within 3–5 minutes</li>
              <li>Normal troponin, normal ECG (no ST changes at rest)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4>🚨 Unstable Angina / NSTEMI / STEMI</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Occurs at rest or with minimal exertion; new onset or worsening</li>
              <li>NOT relieved by rest or 3 NTG doses → medical emergency</li>
              <li>Duration: &gt; 20 minutes</li>
              <li>NSTEMI/STEMI: elevated troponin, ECG changes (ST depression or elevation)</li>
              <li>Requires urgent cardiac catheterization / PCI / thrombolytics</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

